# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: s-parameters
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] In telecommunications, **insertion loss** is the loss of signal power resulting from the insertion of a device in a transmission line or optical fiber and is usually expressed in decibels (dB).
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] Insertion loss is a figure of merit for an electronic filter and this data is generally specified with a filter.
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] Insertion loss is defined as a ratio of the signal level in a test configuration without the filter installed ( $\left\vert V_{1}\right\vert$ ) to the signal level with the filter installed ( $\left\vert V_{2}\right\vert$ ).
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] For passive filters, $\left\vert V_{2}\right\vert$ will be smaller than $\left\vert V_{1}\right\vert$ .
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] In this case, the insertion loss is positive and measures how much smaller the signal is after adding the filter.
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] Here $S_{21}$ is one of the scattering parameters.
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] Insertion loss is the extra loss produced by the introduction of the DUT between the 2 reference planes of the measurement.
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] The extra loss can be introduced by intrinsic loss in the DUT and/or mismatch.
[src:s-parameters/insertion-loss] In case of extra loss the insertion loss is defined to be positive.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] In telecommunications, **return loss** is a measure in relative terms of the power of the signal reflected by a discontinuity in a transmission line or optical fiber.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] This discontinuity can be caused by a mismatch between the termination or load connected to the line and the characteristic impedance of the line.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] where RL(dB) is the return loss in dB, *P*i is the incident power, and *P*r is the reflected power.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] Return loss is related to both standing wave ratio (SWR) and reflection coefficient (Γ).
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] Increasing return loss corresponds to lower SWR.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] Return loss is a measure of how well devices or lines are matched.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] A match is good if the return loss is high.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] A high return loss is desirable and results in a lower insertion loss.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] From a certain perspective "return loss" is a misnomer.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] The usual function of a transmission line is to convey power from a source to a load with minimal loss.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] If a transmission line is correctly matched to a load, the reflected power will be zero, no power will be lost due to reflection, and "return loss" will be infinite.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] Conversely if the line is terminated in an open circuit, the reflected power will be equal to the incident power; all of the incident power will be lost in the sense that none of it will be transferred to a load, and RL will be zero.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] Thus the numerical values of RL tend in the opposite sense to that expected of a "loss".
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] As defined above, RL will always be positive, since *P*r can never exceed *P*i.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] However, return loss has historically been expressed as a negative number, and this convention is still widely found in the literature.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] where RL′(dB) is the negative of RL(dB).
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] In practice, the sign ascribed to RL is largely immaterial.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] If a transmission line includes several discontinuities along its length, the total return loss will be the sum of the RLs caused by each discontinuity, and provided all RLs are given the same sign, no error or ambiguity will result.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] Whichever convention is used, it will always be understood that *P*r can never exceed *P*i.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] In metallic conductor systems, reflections of a signal traveling down a conductor can occur at a discontinuity or impedance mismatch.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] of the amplitude of the reflected wave *V*r to the amplitude of the incident wave *V*i is known as the reflection coefficient.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] Return loss is the negative of the magnitude of the reflection coefficient in dB.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] where the vertical bars indicate magnitude.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] Thus, a large positive return loss indicates that the reflected power is small relative to the incident power, which indicates good impedance match between transmission line and load.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] In optics (particularly in fiber optics) a loss that takes place at discontinuities of refractive index, especially at an air–glass interface such as a fiber endface.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] At those interfaces, a fraction of the optical signal is reflected back toward the source.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] This reflection phenomenon is also called "**Fresnel reflection loss**", or simply "**Fresnel loss**".
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] (where $P_{\text{r}}$ is the reflected power, and $P_{\text{i}}$ is the incident, or input, power) can cause the laser to stop transmitting correctly.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] The measurement of ORL is becoming more important in the characterization of optical networks as the use of wavelength-division multiplexing increases.
[src:s-parameters/return-loss] These systems use lasers that have a lower tolerance for ORL and introduce elements into the network that are located in close proximity to the laser.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The parameters are useful for several branches of electrical engineering, including electronics, communication systems design, and especially for microwave engineering.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The S-parameters are members of a family of similar parameters, other examples being: Y-parameters and Z-parameters, H-parameters, T-parameters and ABCD-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] They differ from these, in the sense that *S-parameters* do not use open or short circuit conditions to characterize a linear electrical network; instead, matched loads are used.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] These terminations are much easier to use at high signal frequencies than open-circuit and short-circuit terminations.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Contrary to popular belief, **the quantities are not measured in terms of power** (except in now-obsolete six-port network analyzers).
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] **Modern vector network analyzers measure amplitude and phase of voltage traveling wave phasors** using essentially the same circuit as that used for the demodulation of digitally modulated wireless signals.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Many electrical properties of networks of components (inductors, capacitors, resistors) may be expressed using S-parameters, such as gain, return loss, voltage standing wave ratio (VSWR), reflection coefficient and amplifier stability.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The term 'scattering' is more common to optical engineering than RF engineering, referring to the effect observed when a plane electromagnetic wave is incident on an obstruction or passes across dissimilar dielectric media.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] In the context of S-parameters, scattering refers to the way in which the traveling currents and voltages in a transmission line are affected when they meet a discontinuity caused by the insertion of a network into the transmission line.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This is equivalent to the wave meeting an impedance differing from the line's characteristic impedance.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Although applicable at any frequency, S-parameters are mostly used for networks operating at radio frequency (RF) and microwave frequencies.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] S-parameters in common use – the conventional S-parameters – are linear quantities (not power quantities, as in the below mentioned 'power waves' approach by Kaneyuki Kurokawa (黒川兼行)).
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] S-parameters change with the measurement frequency, so frequency must be specified for any S-parameter measurements stated, in addition to the characteristic impedance or system impedance.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The first published description of S-parameters was in the thesis of Vitold Belevitch in 1945.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The name used by Belevitch was *repartition matrix* and limited consideration to lumped-element networks.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The term *scattering matrix* was used by physicist and engineer Robert Henry Dicke in 1947 who independently developed the idea during wartime work on radar.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] In these S-parameters and scattering matrices, the scattered waves are the so-called traveling waves.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] A different kind of S-parameters was introduced in the 1960s.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The latter was popularized by Kaneyuki Kurokawa (黒川兼行), who referred to the new scattered waves as 'power waves'.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The two types of S-parameters have very different properties and must not be mixed up.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] In his seminal paper, Kurokawa clearly distinguishes the power-wave S-parameters and the conventional, traveling-wave S-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] A variant of the latter is the pseudo-traveling-wave S-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] In the S-parameter approach, an electrical network is regarded as a 'black box' containing various interconnected basic electrical circuit components or lumped elements such as resistors, capacitors, inductors and transistors, which interacts with other circuits through *ports*.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The network is characterized by a square matrix of complex numbers called its S-parameter matrix, which can be used to calculate its response to signals applied to the ports.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] For the S-parameter definition, it is understood that a network may contain any components provided that the entire network behaves linearly with incident small signals.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] It may also include many typical communication system components or 'blocks' such as amplifiers, attenuators, filters, couplers and equalizers provided they are also operating under linear and defined conditions.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] An electrical network to be described by S-parameters may have any number of ports.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Ports are the points at which electrical signals either enter or exit the network.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Ports are usually pairs of terminals with the requirement that the current into one terminal is equal to the current leaving the other.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] S-parameters are used at frequencies where the ports are often coaxial or waveguide connections.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The S-parameter matrix describing an *N*-port network will be square of dimension *N* and will therefore contain $N^{2}$ elements.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] At the test frequency each element or S-parameter is represented by a unitless complex number that represents magnitude and angle, i.e. amplitude and phase.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The complex number may either be expressed in rectangular form or, more commonly, in polar form.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The S-parameter magnitude may be expressed in linear form or logarithmic form.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] When expressed in logarithmic form, magnitude has the "dimensionless unit" of decibels.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The S-parameter angle is most frequently expressed in degrees but occasionally in radians.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Any S-parameter may be displayed graphically on a polar diagram by a dot for one frequency or a locus for a range of frequencies.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] If it applies to one port only (being of the form $S_{nn}$ ), it may be displayed on an impedance or admittance Smith Chart normalised to the system impedance.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The Smith Chart allows simple conversion between the $S_{nn}$ parameter, equivalent to the voltage reflection coefficient and the associated (normalised) impedance (or admittance) 'seen' at that port.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Conditions which may affect the network, such as temperature, control voltage, and bias current, where applicable.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] For a generic multi-port network, the ports are numbered from 1 to *N*, where *N* is the total number of ports.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] For port *i*, the associated S-parameter definition is in terms of incident and reflected 'power waves', $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ respectively.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Note that as was pointed out by Kurokawa himself, the above definitions of $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ are not unique.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] A network will be reciprocal if it is passive and it contains only reciprocal materials that influence the transmitted signal.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] For example, attenuators, cables, splitters and combiners are all reciprocal networks and $S_{mn}=S_{nm}$ in each case, or the S-parameter matrix will be equal to its transpose.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Networks which include non-reciprocal materials in the transmission medium such as those containing magnetically biased ferrite components will be non-reciprocal.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] An amplifier is another example of a non-reciprocal network.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] A property of 3-port networks, however, is that they cannot be simultaneously reciprocal, loss-free, and perfectly matched.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] A lossless network is one which does not dissipate any power, or: $\Sigma \left|a_{n}\right|^{2}=\Sigma \left|b_{n}\right|^{2}$ .
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The sum of the incident powers at all ports is equal to the sum of the outgoing (e.g.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This implies that the S-parameter matrix is unitary, that is $(S)^{\mathrm {H} }(S)=(I)$ , where $(S)^{\mathrm {H} }$ is the conjugate transpose of $(S)$ and $(I)$ is the identity matrix.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] A lossy passive network is one in which the sum of the incident powers at all ports is greater than the sum of the outgoing (e.g.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The S-parameter matrix for the 2-port network is probably the most commonly used and serves as the basic building block for generating the higher order matrices for larger networks.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Each equation gives the relationship between the outgoing (e.g. reflected) and incident waves at each of the network ports, 1 and 2, in terms of the network's individual S-parameters, $S_{11}$ , $S_{12}$ , $S_{21}$ and $S_{22}$ .
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] If one considers an incident wave at port 1 ( $a_{1}$ ) there may result from it waves exiting from either port 1 itself ( $b_{1}$ ) or port 2 ( $b_{2}$ ).
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] However, if, according to the definition of S-parameters, port 2 is terminated in a load identical to the system impedance ( $Z_{0}$ ) then, by the maximum power transfer theorem, $b_{2}$ will be totally absorbed making $a_{2}$ equal to zero.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] is the output port voltage reflection coefficient.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] If, instead of defining the voltage wave direction relative to each port, they are defined by their absolute direction as forward $V^{+}$ and reverse $V^{-}$ waves then $b_{2}=V_{2}^{+}$ and $a_{1}=V_{1}^{+}$ .
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The S-parameters then take on a more intuitive meaning such as the forward voltage gain being defined by the ratio of the forward voltages $S_{21}=V_{2}^{+}/V_{1}^{+}$ .
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] An amplifier operating under linear (small signal) conditions is a good example of a non-reciprocal network and a matched attenuator is an example of a reciprocal network.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] In the following cases we will assume that the input and output connections are to ports 1 and 2 respectively which is the most common convention.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The nominal system impedance, frequency and any other factors which may influence the device, such as temperature, must also be specified.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] That is the linear ratio of the output reflected power wave divided by the input incident power wave, all values expressed as complex quantities.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] For lossy networks it is sub-unitary, for active networks $|G|>1$ .
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] It will be equal to the voltage gain only when the device has equal input and output impedances.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This represents the gain magnitude (absolute value), the ratio of the output power-wave to the input power-wave, and it equals the square-root of the power gain.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This is a real-value (or scalar) quantity, the phase information being dropped.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This is more commonly used than scalar linear gain and a positive quantity is normally understood as simply a "gain", while a negative quantity is a "negative gain" (a "loss"), equivalent to its magnitude in dB.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] For example, at 100 MHz, a 10 m length of cable may have a gain of −1 dB, equal to a loss of 1 dB.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] In case the two measurement ports use the same reference impedance, the insertion loss (*IL*) is the reciprocal of the magnitude of the transmission coefficient |*S*21| expressed in decibels.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] It is the extra loss produced by the introduction of the device under test (DUT) between the 2 reference planes of the measurement.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The extra loss may be due to intrinsic loss in the DUT and/or mismatch.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The negative of insertion loss expressed in decibels is defined as insertion gain and is equal to the scalar logarithmic gain (see: definition above).
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Input return loss (*RL*in) can be thought of as a measure of how close the actual input impedance of the network is to the nominal system impedance value.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Note that for passive two-port networks in which |*S*11| ≤ 1, it follows that return loss is a non-negative quantity: *RLin* ≥ 0.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Also note that somewhat confusingly, return loss is sometimes used as the negative of the quantity defined above, but this usage is, strictly speaking, incorrect based on the definition of loss.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The output return loss (*RL*out) has a similar definition to the input return loss but applies to the output port (port 2) instead of the input port.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] We can see that for the perfectly matched case, where $\Gamma _{L}=\Gamma _{S}=0$ , these equations collapse down as expected to give $S_{11}$ and $S_{22}$ respectively.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The voltage standing wave ratio (VSWR) at a port, represented by the lower case 's', is a similar measure of port match to return loss but is a scalar linear quantity, the ratio of the standing wave maximum voltage to the standing wave minimum voltage.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] It therefore relates to the magnitude of the voltage reflection coefficient and hence to the magnitude of either $S_{11}$ for the input port or $S_{22}$ for the output port.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This is correct for reflection coefficients with a magnitude no greater than unity, which is usually the case.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] A reflection coefficient with a magnitude greater than unity, such as in a tunnel diode amplifier, will result in a negative value for this expression.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] VSWR, however, from its definition, is always positive.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] 4-port S-parameters are used to characterize 4-port networks.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] They include information regarding the reflected and incident power waves between the four ports of the network.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] They are commonly used to analyze a pair of coupled transmission lines to determine the amount of cross-talk between them, if they are driven by two separate single ended signals, or the reflected and incident power of a differential signal driven across them.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Many specifications of high speed differential signals define a communication channel in terms of the 4-port S-parameters, for example the 10-Gigabit Attachment Unit Interface (XAUI), SATA, PCI-X, and InfiniBand systems.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] 4-port mixed-mode S-parameters characterize a 4-port network in terms of the response of the network to common mode and differential stimulus signals.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The following table displays the 4-port mixed-mode S-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Note the format of the parameter notation SXYab, where "S" stands for scattering parameter or S-parameter, "X" is the response mode (differential or common), "Y" is the stimulus mode (differential or common), "a" is the response (output) port and b is the stimulus (input) port.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This is the typical nomenclature for scattering parameters.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The first quadrant is defined as the upper left 4 parameters describing the differential stimulus and differential response characteristics of the device under test.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This is the actual mode of operation for most high-speed differential interconnects and is the quadrant that receives the most attention.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] It includes input differential return loss (SDD11), input differential insertion loss (SDD21), output differential return loss (SDD22) and output differential insertion loss (SDD12).
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The second and third quadrants are the upper right and lower left 4 parameters respectively.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] These are also referred to as the cross-mode quadrants.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Understanding mode conversion is very helpful when trying to optimize the design of interconnects for gigabit data throughput.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The fourth quadrant is the lower right 4 parameters and describes the performance characteristics of the common-mode signal SCCab propagating through the device under test.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] For a properly designed SDDab differential device there should be minimal common-mode output SCCab.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] However, the fourth quadrant common-mode response data is a measure of common-mode transmission response and used in a ratio with the differential transmission response to determine the network common-mode rejection.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This common mode rejection is an important benefit of differential signal processing and can be reduced to one in some differential circuit implementations.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The reverse isolation parameter $S_{12}$ determines the level of feedback from the output of an amplifier to the input and therefore influences its stability (its tendency to refrain from oscillation) together with the forward gain $S_{21}$ .
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] An amplifier with input and output ports perfectly isolated from each other would have infinite scalar log magnitude isolation or the linear magnitude of $S_{12}$ would be zero.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Such an amplifier is said to be unilateral.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Most practical amplifiers though will have some finite isolation allowing the reflection coefficient 'seen' at the input to be influenced to some extent by the load connected on the output.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] An amplifier which is deliberately designed to have the smallest possible value of $\left|S_{12}\right|$ is often called a buffer amplifier.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Suppose the output port of a real (non-unilateral or bilateral) amplifier is connected to an arbitrary load with a reflection coefficient of $\Gamma _{L}$ .
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] If the amplifier is unilateral then $S_{12}=0$ and $\Gamma _{\mathrm {in} }=S_{11}$ or, to put it another way, the output loading has no effect on the input.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] A similar property exists in the opposite direction, in this case if $\Gamma _{\mathrm {out} }$ is the reflection coefficient seen at the output port and $\Gamma _{s}$ is the reflection coefficient of the source connected to the input port.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] An amplifier is unconditionally stable if a load or source of *any* reflection coefficient can be connected without causing instability.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This condition occurs if the magnitudes of the reflection coefficients at the source, load and the amplifier's input and output ports are simultaneously less than unity.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] An important requirement that is often overlooked is that the amplifier be a linear network with no poles in the right half plane.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Instability can cause severe distortion of the amplifier's gain frequency response or, in the extreme, oscillation.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The boundary condition for when each of these values is equal to unity may be represented by a circle drawn on the polar diagram representing the (complex) reflection coefficient, one for the input port and the other for the output port.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Often these will be scaled as Smith Charts.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] and the superscript star (*) indicates a complex conjugate.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The circles are in complex units of reflection coefficient so may be drawn on impedance or admittance based Smith charts normalised to the system impedance.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This serves to readily show the regions of normalised impedance (or admittance) for predicted unconditional stability.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The scattering transfer parameters or T-parameters of a 2-port network are expressed by the T-parameter matrix and are closely related to the corresponding S-parameter matrix.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] However, unlike S-parameters, there is no simple physical means to measure the T-parameters in a system, sometimes referred to as Youla waves.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The RF Toolbox add-on to MATLAB and several books (for example "Network scattering parameters") use this last definition, so caution is necessary.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The "From S to T" and "From T to S" paragraphs in this article are based on the first definition.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Adaptation to the second definition is trivial (interchanging T11 for T22, and T12 for T21).
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The advantage of T-parameters compared to S-parameters is that providing reference impedances are purely, real or complex conjugate, they may be used to readily determine the effect of cascading 2 or more 2-port networks by simply multiplying the associated individual T-parameter matrices.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Note that matrix multiplication is not commutative, so the order is important.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] As with S-parameters, T-parameters are complex values and there is a direct conversion between the two types.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] However once the operation is completed, the complex full wave interactions between all ports in both directions will be taken into account.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The following equations will provide conversion between S and T parameters for 2-port networks.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The S-parameter for a 1-port network is given by a simple 1 × 1 matrix of the form $(s_{nn})$ where n is the allocated port number.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] To comply with the S-parameter definition of linearity, this would normally be a passive load of some type.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] An antenna is a common one-port network for which small values of $s_{11}$ indicate that the antenna will either radiate or dissipate/store power.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] In this way the incident power wave for each of the unused ports becomes zero yielding similar expressions to those obtained for the 2-port case.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] S-parameters relating to single ports only ( $S_{mm}$ ) require all of the remaining ports to be loaded with an impedance identical to the system impedance therefore making all of the incident power waves zero except that for the port under consideration.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] where $S_{mn}$ refers to the outgoing wave at port *m* induced by the incident wave at port *n*.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] S-parameters are most commonly measured with a vector network analyzer (VNA).
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Once determined, the S-parameters of a device may be saved in several different formats.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Often they are simply tabulated against frequency in a Touchstone file, also known as an S*n*P file, where *n* is the number of ports.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] These are specifically formatted text files with the filename extension '.s1p', '.s2p' etc.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] This format is standardised by the IBIS Open Forum and was updated in January 2024.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Any 2-port S-parameter may also be displayed on a polar diagram using polar co-ordinates.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] In either graphical format, the S-parameters are typically plotted as a sweep across the frequency range of interest.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] VNAs designed for the simultaneous measurement of the S-parameters of networks with more than two ports are feasible but quickly become prohibitively complex and expensive.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Usually their purchase is not justified since the required measurements can be obtained using a standard 2-port calibrated VNA with extra measurements followed by the correct interpretation of the results obtained.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] The required S-parameter matrix can be assembled from successive two port measurements in stages, two ports at a time, on each occasion with the unused ports being terminated in high quality loads equal to the system impedance.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] One risk of this approach is that the return loss or VSWR of the loads themselves must be suitably specified to be as close as possible to a perfect 50 Ohms, or whatever the nominal system impedance is.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] For a network with many ports there may be a temptation, on grounds of cost, to inadequately specify the VSWRs of the loads.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Some analysis will be necessary to determine what the worst acceptable VSWR of the loads will be.
[src:s-parameters/scattering-parameters] Assuming that the extra loads are specified adequately, if necessary, two or more of the S-parameter subscripts are modified from those relating to the VNA (1 and 2 in the case considered above) to those relating to the network under test (1 to N, if N is the total number of DUT ports).
