[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] In the differential amplifier application, a large output resistance increases the difference-mode gain, a good thing, and a small mirror input resistance is desirable to avoid Miller effect.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] All the *Y*-parameters have dimensions of siemens.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] For reciprocal lossless networks all the *y*mn are purely imaginary.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] This circuit is often selected when a current amplifier is desired at the output.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The resistors shown in the diagram can be general impedances instead.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Off-diagonal h-parameters are dimensionless, while diagonal members have dimensions the reciprocal of one another.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] For reciprocal lossless networks *h*12 and *h*21 are real, while *h*11 and *h*22 are purely imaginary.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The h-parameters were initially called *series-parallel parameters*.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The term *hybrid* to describe these parameters was coined by D.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Alsberg in 1953 in "Transistor metrology".
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] In 1954 a joint committee of the IRE and the AIEE adopted the term h-*parameters* and recommended that these become the standard method of testing and characterising transistors because they were "peculiarly adaptable to the physical characteristics of transistors".
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] In 1956, the recommendation became an issued standard; 56 IRE 28.S2.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Following the merge of these two organisations as the IEEE, the standard became Std 218-1956 and was reaffirmed in 1980, but has now been withdrawn.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Often this circuit is selected when a voltage amplifier is wanted at the output.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Off-diagonal g-parameters are dimensionless, while diagonal members have dimensions the reciprocal of one another.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The ABCD-parameters are known variously as chain, cascade, or transmission parameters.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Note: Some authors chose to reverse the indicated direction of I2 and suppress the negative sign on I2.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] For reciprocal networks *AD* – *BC* = 1.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] For networks which are reciprocal and lossless, A and D are purely real while B and C are purely imaginary.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] This representation is preferred because when the parameters are used to represent a cascade of two-ports, the matrices are written in the same order that a network diagram would be drawn, that is, left to right.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The negative sign of –*I*2 arises to make the output current of one cascaded stage (as it appears in the matrix) equal to the input current of the next.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Without the minus sign the two currents would have opposite senses because the positive direction of current, by convention, is taken as the current entering the port.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Consequently, the input voltage/current matrix vector can be directly replaced with the matrix equation of the preceding cascaded stage to form a combined A'B'C'D' matrix.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The terminology of representing the ABCD parameters as a matrix of elements designated *a*11 etc. as adopted by some authors and the inverse A'B'C'D' parameters as a matrix of elements designated *b*11 etc. is used here for both brevity and to avoid confusion with circuit elements.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The table below lists ABCD and inverse ABCD parameters for some simple network elements.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The previous parameters are all defined in terms of voltages and currents at ports.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] S-parameters are different, and are defined in terms of incident and reflected waves at ports.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] S-parameters are used primarily at UHF and microwave frequencies where it becomes difficult to measure voltages and currents directly.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] On the other hand, incident and reflected power are easy to measure using directional couplers.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] where the ak are the incident waves and the bk are the reflected waves at port k.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] It is conventional to define the ak and bk in terms of the square root of power.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Consequently, there is a relationship with the wave voltages (see main article for details).
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] For antimetrical networks *S*11 = –*S*22.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Scattering transfer parameters, like scattering parameters, are defined in terms of incident and reflected waves.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The difference is that T-parameters relate the waves at port 1 to the waves at port 2 whereas S-parameters relate the reflected waves to the incident waves.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] In this respect T-parameters fill the same role as ABCD parameters and allow the T-parameters of cascaded networks to be calculated by matrix multiplication of the component networks.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] T-parameters, like ABCD parameters, can also be called transmission parameters.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] T-parameters are not as easy to measure directly as S-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] However, S-parameters are easily converted to T-parameters, see main article for details.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] When two or more two-port networks are connected, the two-port parameters of the combined network can be found by performing matrix algebra on the matrices of parameters for the component two-ports.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The matrix operation can be made particularly simple with an appropriate choice of two-port parameters to match the form of connection of the two-ports.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] For instance, the z-parameters are best for series connected ports.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The combination rules need to be applied with care.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Some connections (when dissimilar potentials are joined) result in the port condition being invalidated and the combination rule will no longer apply.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] A Brune test can be used to check the permissibility of the combination.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] This difficulty can be overcome by placing 1:1 ideal transformers on the outputs of the problem two-ports.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] This does not change the parameters of the two-ports, but does ensure that they will continue to meet the port condition when interconnected.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] An example of this problem is shown for series-series connections in figures 11 and 12 below.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] When two-ports are connected in a series-series configuration as shown in figure 10, the best choice of two-port parameter is the z-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The z-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix addition of the two individual z-parameter matrices.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] As mentioned above, there are some networks which will not yield directly to this analysis.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] A simple example is a two-port consisting of a L-network of resistors *R*1 and *R*2.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Figure 11 shows two identical such networks connected in series-series.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The discrepancy is explained by observing that *R*1 of the lower two-port has been by-passed by the short-circuit between two terminals of the output ports.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] This results in no current flowing through one terminal in each of the input ports of the two individual networks.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Consequently, the port condition is broken for both the input ports of the original networks since current is still able to flow into the other terminal.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] This problem can be resolved by inserting an ideal transformer in the output port of at least one of the two-port networks.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] While this is a common text-book approach to presenting the theory of two-ports, the practicality of using transformers is a matter to be decided for each individual design.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] When two-ports are connected in a parallel-parallel configuration as shown in figure 13, the best choice of two-port parameter is the y-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The y-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix addition of the two individual y-parameter matrices.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] When two-ports are connected in a series-parallel configuration as shown in figure 14, the best choice of two-port parameter is the h-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The h-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix addition of the two individual h-parameter matrices.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] When two-ports are connected in a parallel-series configuration as shown in figure 15, the best choice of two-port parameter is the g-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The g-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix addition of the two individual g-parameter matrices.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] When two-ports are connected with the output port of the first connected to the input port of the second (a cascade connection) as shown in figure 16, the best choice of two-port parameter is the ABCD-parameters.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The a-parameters of the combined network are found by matrix multiplication of the two individual a-parameter matrices.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] A chain of n two-ports may be combined by matrix multiplication of the n matrices.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Suppose we have a two-port network consisting of a series resistor R followed by a shunt capacitor C.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] Certain pairs of matrices have a particularly simple relationship.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The admittance parameters are the matrix inverse of the impedance parameters, the inverse hybrid parameters are the matrix inverse of the hybrid parameters, and the [**b**] form of the ABCD-parameters is the matrix inverse of the [**a**] form.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] While two port networks are very common (e.g., amplifiers and filters), other electrical networks such as directional couplers and circulators have more than 2 ports.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] A two-port network has four variables with two of them being independent.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] If one of the ports is terminated by a load with no independent sources, then the load enforces a relationship between the voltage and current of that port.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The circuit now has only one independent parameter.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The two-port becomes a one-port impedance to the remaining independent variable.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] The negative sign is because the positive direction for *I*2 is directed into the two-port instead of into the load.
[src:s-parameters/two-port-network] So, in effect, *I*1 sees an input impedance *Z*in and the two-port's effect on the input circuit has been effectively collapsed down to a one-port; i.e., a simple two terminal impedance.
